In [[economics]], '''free contract''' is the concept that people may decide what [[Contract|agreements]] they want to enter into.<ref>{{cite book | last = O'Sullivan | first = Arthur | authorlink = Arthur O'Sullivan (economist) | first2 = Steven M. | last2 = Sheffrin | title = Economics: Principles in Action | publisher = Pearson Prentice Hall | year = 2003 | location = Upper Saddle River, New Jersey 07458 | pages = 551 | isbn = 0-13-063085-3}}</ref>
A [[contract]] may be described as ''free'' when it is free from force or fraud.<ref name="Ryan1916">{{cite book|last=Ryan|first=John Augustine|title=Distributive justice: the right and wrong of our present distribution of wealth|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EjQJAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA328|accessdate=7 December 2010|year=1916|publisher=Macmillan|page=328}}</ref>
